  3. ## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
    ## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   marital       perc_happy
##   <fct>              <dbl>
## 1 Never married      0.839
## 2 Married            0.923
## 3 Separated          0.717
## 4 Divorced           0.810
## 5 Widowed            0.804

    Individuals who never married tend to be happy. 10686 out of 12741 (83.87%) of these individuals indicated that they were pretty happy or very happy. Married individuals tend to be happy. 29342 out of 34129 of these individuals indicated that they were pretty happy or very happy. Separated individuals tend to be mostly pretty happy followed by not too happy. Divorced individuals tend to be pretty happy. Widowed individuals tend to be pretty happy.

  5. ## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
    ## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   marital       mean_educ
##   <fct>             <dbl>
## 1 No answer          15.5
## 2 Never married      13.4
## 3 Married            13.0
## 4 Separated          11.9
## 5 Divorced           13.1
## 6 Widowed            11.2

    The histograms above appear to show that regardless of marital status, the distribution of number of years completed in school is relatively the same. Widowed and separated have the widest range of number of years completed in school. Based on the table, those who chose not to answer completed the highest years of education with an average of 15.5 years, followed by never married, divorced, married, separated, then widowed.
